 abstract = {The aggregation of coronene is relevant to understand the formation of carbon nanomaterials, including graphene quantum dots (GQDs) that show exceptional photophysical properties. This article evaluates the influence of carboxyl and amine substituting groups on the aggregation of coronene by performing a global optimization study based on a new potential energy surface. The structures of clusters with substituted coronene are similar to those formed by un-substituted monomers, that is, stacked (non-stacked) motifs are favoured for small-size (large-size) clusters. Nonetheless, the presence of carboxyl and amine groups leads to an increase of the number of local minima of comparable energy. The clusters with substituted monomers have also shown to enhance the attractive component interaction, which can be attributed to weak induction and charge transfer effects and to stronger electrostatic contributions. Moreover, the calculated height of magic-number structures of the clusters in this work is compatible with the morphology of the GQDs reported in the literature.},
